Fukushima and the collapse of derivatives
CAMBRIDGE – Financial commentators have compared the Japanese earthquake, tsunami, and nuclear disaster to the role of derivatives in the 2008 financial crisis.
The resemblance is quite clear: each of these activities generates large profits and involves a very low but explosive risk.
Yet, the similarity between the two types of crisis ends where the way to prevent their recurrence begins.
In the case of the Fukushima nuclear plant, a once-in-a-century flood, combined with usually harmless design flaws, caused the shutdown of cooling water circulation in the reactors and significant radiation leaks.
With regard to financial markets, an unexpected collapse in real estate values, combined with design flaws in the derivatives and repo markets, has damaged the ability of major financial institutions to meet their debts.
Although the basic risks originate outside the systems – a tsunami for Fukushima, excessive investment in mortgage-backed securities for financial institutions – design flaws and a lack of luck have caused the systems to be unable to contain the damage.
In the United States, AIG, Bear Stearns and Lehman Brothers – all with significant investments in derivatives and/or repos – went bankrupt, causing a credit freeze on the markets for several long weeks.
We now understand fairly well the risks and design flaws of Fukushima.
We cannot say the same about the risks of derivatives that caused the global economy to wobble.
At Fukushima, teams of workers are bravely trying to stop the radiation leaks.
However, for derivatives, similar efforts are misdirected and will not allow us to avoid the next financial crisis.
We are recreating similar derivatives and financial structures, on top of the same errors that are still active.
Financial actors use financial instruments to transfer risk: for example, one actor accepts the risk of euro fluctuations but does not want the risk on the yen, while for another, it will be the opposite.
In this case, the first promises to provide euros on June 1st, and the second promises to provide yen.
If one currency loses value compared to the other, the loser pays the difference.
Repos are financial transactions.
Financial firms sell assets, such as Treasury bills or mortgage-backed debts, for cash and promise to repurchase these assets later, typically the next day (hence the name "repo," which is an abbreviation for the English verb repurchase – or repurchase, ndt).
The problem is that the cash coming from these short-term repos represents a large part of the balance sheets of the most important financial institutions, which implies that even minor financial tremors can strongly affect them.
Some institutions can then find themselves deprived of repo financing, as in 2008, and go bankrupt, like Bear Stearns.
Taken individually, transactions in derivatives or repos are not really to blame.
Each one separately legitimately transfers risk to those better able to bear it, or allows for financial participation.
However, when they are used excessively by institutions that are systemically vital, they can cause the financial system to explode, due to its design flaws.
Even today, approximately 70% of the liabilities of major American financial firms are made up of very short-term loans, such as repos payable the next day.
In the United States, the main design flaws are found in bankruptcy legislation, which exempts derivatives and repos from most usual constraints in the event of bankruptcy.
For example, investors who hold derivatives or repo contracts with financially weakened institutions can seize the company's assets before – and at the expense of – its normal creditors. In doing so, they can decide the company's fate, even though, with a little more time, the company in question could have survived.
Such actions ruined AIG, Bear Stearns, and others during the financial crisis.
Worse still, because investors in derivatives and repos end up at the head of the line for repayments in so many ways, they have less incentive to encourage market discipline by closely checking the solvency of their counterparties and carefully rationing their exposure to any single counterparty.
Typically, they will be repaid, anyway.
Certainly, someone has to be first.
Other financial actors must bear more risk because the exemptions of derivatives and repo actors place them at the front of the line in case of bankruptcy.
Normally, one would expect these others to therefore have an interest in encouraging more market discipline.
But the actor who follows in line is too often the American government, as the guarantor of "too-big-to-fail" financial institutions (too important to let fail, ndt). However, the government is poorly positioned to regulate these markets on a daily basis.
It is not financially agile; it often confines itself to the regulated market; and, when economic conditions are good, no official would want to spoil the party.
The American Congress had an opportunity to fix this flaw in the major overhaul of finance that it adopted last summer via the Dodd Frank bill.
But he did not grasp it.
If investors in derivatives, repos, and credit-default swaps (credit event derivatives, ndt) did not benefit from preferential treatment, they would behave differently.
First and foremost, they would more often insist that their counterparties be adequately capitalized.
They accepted the risk generated by ultra-low capitalization when it essentially involved American government money; they would be less inclined to do so if it was their own money at stake.
The public perceives Fukushima-type risks and risks related to derivatives differently.
Many people fear nuclear risks, which are striking, causing a slowdown in the sector that must deal with security concerns.
But the derivatives and repo markets present risks that are poorly understood, difficult to communicate in the media, and complicated to debate and resolve for politicians.
During a crisis, these markets attract public attention and disdain, but when the economy stabilizes again, ordinary people lose all interest, leaving the financial sector to control its own destiny with the legislative body.
Regarding Fukushima-type risks, analysts are already discussing how nuclear plants can be designed and built to contain risks related to earthquakes and tsunamis through passive cooling systems.
Today, it is considered possible to design nuclear plants capable of keeping the fuel rods cool even in the event of a complete power outage.
On the contrary, few significant advances have been made so far in order to prevent the damage that the priority of derivatives and repos in the event of bankruptcy could cause during a new financial system crisis.
New rules are being developed, which require end-users (such as oil companies using derivatives to protect themselves from unanticipated changes in oil prices) and others to post high-quality collateral.
However, these rules do not address the main problem: the weak incentives for market discipline for the main financial institutions.
It is as if we were reacting to Fukushima by better controlling gas emissions in oil extraction projects.
We should examine how to fully make investors in derivatives and repos bear the risk related to their decisions when they conduct transactions with financial institutions that are systemically vital.
Instead, we have survived the financial tsunami of 2008 only to rebuild in the same place, with the same financial flaws and according to the same defective design.
